Classical Mechanics.description: Branch of physics studying motion of bodies under forces. Key laws: Newton's three laws, conservation of momentum. Applications: engineering, motion prediction, robotics.

Thermodynamics.description: Study of heat, energy, and work. Key concepts: first, second, third laws; entropy; enthalpy. Applications: engines, refrigeration, energy efficiency.

Optics.description: Study of light propagation, reflection, refraction, diffraction, and interference. Applications: lenses, cameras, fiber optics, lasers.

Electromagnetism.description: Study of electric and magnetic fields and their interactions. Governed by Maxwell's equations. Applications: circuits, telecommunications, motors, MRI.

Quantum Mechanics.description: Physics of particles at atomic and subatomic scales. Key concepts: wavefunction, uncertainty principle, superposition. Applications: semiconductors, quantum computing, spectroscopy.

Relativity.description: Einsteins theories: special relativity (motion at high speeds) and general relativity (gravity as spacetime curvature). Applications: GPS, astrophysics, cosmology.

Particle Physics.description: Study of fundamental particles and forces. Includes quarks, leptons, bosons. Applications: collider experiments, standard model, Higgs mechanism.

Nuclear Physics.description: Study of atomic nuclei, radioactive decay, nuclear reactions. Applications: energy generation, medical imaging, nuclear medicine.

Acoustics.description: Science of sound waves: production, transmission, reception. Applications: audio engineering, noise control, sonar.

Fluid Mechanics.description: Study of fluids (liquids, gases) and forces on them. Principles: continuity, Bernoulli, Navier-Stokes. Applications: aerodynamics, hydraulics, meteorology.

Astrophysics.description: Study of physics governing celestial bodies and cosmic phenomena. Applications: star and galaxy formation, black holes, cosmology.

Cosmology.description: Study of the origin, structure, evolution, and fate of the universe. Applications: theoretical physics, astronomy, dark matter and dark energy research.

Quantum Entanglement.description: Particles linked such that measurement of one affects the other instantaneously. Applications: quantum computing, secure communication, teleportation.

Schrodinger Equation.description: Fundamental quantum mechanics equation describing wavefunction evolution: i /t = H. Applications: atomic/molecular modeling, quantum simulations.

Black Holes.description: Dense spacetime regions with gravity so strong nothing escapes. Applications: astrophysics, gravitational wave detection.

Higgs Boson.description: Fundamental particle giving mass to others via Higgs field. Discovered at CERN, 2012. Applications: particle physics, standard model validation.

Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle.description: Impossible to measure exact position and momentum simultaneously: x * p  /2. Applications: quantum measurement, particle confinement.

Quantum Gravity.description: Theoretical attempt to unify quantum mechanics and general relativity. Approaches: string theory, loop quantum gravity.

Special Relativity.description: Theory describing physics at speeds close to light. Key concepts: time dilation, length contraction, mass-energy equivalence. Applications: particle accelerators, GPS, astrophysics.

General Relativity.description: Theory describing gravity as curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy. Applications: cosmology, black holes, gravitational waves.

Statistical Mechanics.description: Study of large ensembles of particles and their collective behavior. Key concepts: microstates, macrostates, partition function. Applications: thermodynamics, phase transitions, material science.

Condensed Matter Physics.description: Study of physical properties of solids and liquids. Topics: superconductivity, magnetism, crystallography. Applications: electronics, materials, nanotechnology.

Plasma Physics.description: Study of ionized gases and collective behavior of charged particles. Applications: fusion energy, astrophysics, space physics.

Optical Physics.description: Branch of physics focusing on light properties, photon behavior, and laser-matter interactions. Applications: spectroscopy, fiber optics, laser technology.

Acoustic Engineering.description: Application of acoustics in designing sound systems, noise reduction, and vibration control. Applications: concert halls, audio devices, sonar systems.

Fluid Dynamics.description: Detailed study of fluids in motion including turbulence, laminar flow, and Navier-Stokes equations. Applications: aerodynamics, hydraulics, climate modeling.

Computational Physics.description: Use of numerical methods and simulations to solve physical problems. Applications: astrophysics simulations, quantum modeling, material science.

High Energy Physics.description: Study of particle interactions at very high energies. Topics: collider experiments, particle decays, symmetry breaking. Applications: standard model tests, discovery of new particles.

Quantum Field Theory.description: Framework combining quantum mechanics and special relativity to describe particle physics. Applications: particle interactions, gauge theories, electroweak unification.

Gravitational Waves.description: Ripples in spacetime caused by accelerating massive objects. Applications: astrophysics, black hole mergers, cosmology.

Cosmic Rays.description: High-energy particles from space interacting with Earths atmosphere. Applications: astrophysics, particle detectors, space weather studies.

Dark Matter.description: Hypothetical matter that does not emit light but exerts gravitational effects. Applications: galaxy formation studies, cosmology.

Dark Energy.description: Unknown energy component causing accelerated expansion of the universe. Applications: cosmology, theoretical physics.

Magnetohydrodynamics.description: Study of dynamics of electrically conducting fluids in magnetic fields. Applications: astrophysics, fusion reactors, space plasma studies.

Wave-Particle Duality.description: Concept that particles exhibit both wave and particle properties. Applications: quantum experiments, electron diffraction, photon behavior.

Quantum Computing.description: Computation using quantum-mechanical phenomena such as superposition and entanglement. Applications: cryptography, optimization, simulation of quantum systems.

Laser Physics.description: Study of coherent light generation and manipulation. Applications: communications, medicine, industry, research.

Time Crystals.description: Novel phase of matter exhibiting periodic structure in time. Applications: quantum computing, condensed matter research.

Algebra.description: Study of mathematical symbols and rules for manipulating them. Includes equations, polynomials, matrices. Applications: problem solving, computer algorithms, engineering.

Geometry.description: Study of shapes, sizes, and properties of space. Branches: Euclidean, non-Euclidean, differential geometry. Applications: architecture, computer graphics, navigation.

Calculus.description: Study of continuous change: derivatives, integrals, limits, series. Applications: physics, optimization, modeling natural phenomena.

Linear Algebra.description: Study of vectors, matrices, linear transformations, vector spaces. Applications: computer graphics, machine learning, data science.

Probability Theory.description: Mathematical study of random events and likelihood. Concepts: probability distributions, expectation, variance. Applications: statistics, risk analysis, AI.

Statistics.description: Collection, analysis, interpretation, and presentation of data. Techniques: regression, hypothesis testing, ANOVA. Applications: research, quality control, forecasting.

Topology.description: Study of properties preserved under continuous deformations: stretching, twisting, bending. Applications: network analysis, material science, geometry.

Number Theory.description: Study of integers and integer-valued functions. Topics: primes, modular arithmetic, Diophantine equations. Applications: cryptography, coding theory.

Combinatorics.description: Mathematical study of counting, arrangement, and combination. Applications: probability, computer science, optimization.

Differential Equations.description: Equations involving derivatives describing change of systems. Types: ordinary, partial. Applications: physics, engineering, biology.

Fourier Analysis.description: Study of representing functions as sums of sines/cosines. Applications: signal processing, heat transfer, quantum mechanics.

Complex Analysis.description: Study of functions of complex numbers. Applications: fluid dynamics, electrical engineering, applied mathematics.

Set Theory.description: Study of sets, collections of objects. Concepts: unions, intersections, power sets. Applications: logic, foundations of mathematics, probability.

Mathematical Logic.description: Study of formal systems, proofs, and reasoning. Includes propositional and predicate logic. Applications: computer science, theorem proving, AI.

Abstract Algebra.description: Study of algebraic structures such as groups, rings, and fields. Applications: cryptography, coding theory, advanced mathematics.

Graph Theory.description: Study of graphs as mathematical structures modeling pairwise relations. Applications: networks, computer science, optimization.

Optimization.description: Study of finding maxima and minima of functions subject to constraints. Applications: economics, engineering, operations research.

Game Theory.description: Mathematical study of strategic decision making among rational agents. Applications: economics, political science, AI.

Numerical Analysis.description: Study of algorithms for approximating solutions to mathematical problems. Applications: simulations, engineering computations, scientific computing.

Mathematical Modeling.description: Creating mathematical representations of real-world systems. Applications: physics, biology, finance, social sciences.

Tensor Calculus.description: Study of tensors and their transformations, used in differential geometry and relativity. Applications: general relativity, continuum mechanics, physics.

Measure Theory.description: Study of measures, integration, and probability foundations. Applications: probability theory, functional analysis, statistics.

Functional Analysis.description: Study of vector spaces with limits, norms, and linear operators. Applications: quantum mechanics, PDEs, optimization.

Chaos Theory.description: Study of systems highly sensitive to initial conditions. Applications: meteorology, finance, population dynamics.

Fractal Geometry.description: Study of self-similar structures and non-integer dimensions. Applications: computer graphics, natural phenomena modeling.

Cell Biology.description: Study of cell structure and function. Includes organelles, cytoskeleton, cell cycle. Applications: medicine, biotechnology, molecular biology.

Genetics.description: Study of genes, heredity, and variation. Includes Mendelian inheritance, DNA mutations, genome sequencing. Applications: medicine, agriculture, evolution.

Molecular Biology.description: Study of molecular mechanisms of biological activity. Includes DNA, RNA, proteins. Applications: gene therapy, drug development, biotechnology.

Evolution.description: Change in heritable traits over generations. Mechanisms: natural selection, genetic drift, mutations. Applications: ecology, medicine, conservation.

Ecology.description: Study of interactions between organisms and environment. Concepts: ecosystems, food chains, biodiversity. Applications: conservation, agriculture, climate research.

Physiology.description: Study of functions of organs and systems in living organisms. Applications: medicine, sports science, research.

Neurobiology.description: Study of the nervous system structure and function. Topics: neurons, synapses, brain regions. Applications: medicine, AI inspiration, cognitive science.

Microbiology.description: Study of microorganisms: bacteria, viruses, fungi, protozoa. Applications: medicine, food safety, biotechnology.

Immunology.description: Study of immune system and responses. Includes innate and adaptive immunity, antibodies, vaccines. Applications: disease prevention, immunotherapy, epidemiology.

Cellular Respiration.description: Conversion of glucose and oxygen into ATP, CO2, and water. Processes: glycolysis, Krebs cycle, oxidative phosphorylation. Applications: bioenergetics, physiology, biotechnology.

Photosynthesis.description: Conversion of light energy, CO2, and water into glucose and oxygen in plants. Applications: agriculture, bioenergy, climate studies.

Developmental Biology.description: Study of organism growth and development from fertilization to adulthood. Applications: regenerative medicine, embryology, genetics.

Biochemistry.description: Study of chemical processes in living organisms. Includes proteins, nucleic acids, enzymes, metabolism. Applications: medicine, nutrition, biotechnology.

Endocrinology.description: Study of hormones, endocrine glands, and their physiological effects. Applications: diabetes management, metabolic disorders, reproductive health.

Cardiology.description: Study of heart structure, function, and cardiovascular diseases. Applications: diagnosis, treatment, prevention of heart diseases.

Virology.description: Study of viruses and virus-like agents, their structure, replication, and pathology. Applications: vaccine development, epidemiology, antiviral therapies.

Parasitology.description: Study of parasites, their hosts, and the relationship between them. Applications: disease control, epidemiology, veterinary medicine.

Oncology.description: Study of cancer, including tumor development, progression, and treatment. Applications: diagnosis, chemotherapy, radiotherapy, research.

Genomics.description: Study of genomes, DNA sequencing, and functional analysis of genes. Applications: personalized medicine, evolutionary studies, disease research.

Proteomics.description: Study of the structure and function of proteins and protein interactions. Applications: drug discovery, biomarker identification, molecular biology.

Neurophysiology.description: Study of the function of the nervous system and neural circuits. Applications: neuroscience research, clinical neurology, cognitive studies.

Pathology.description: Study of disease mechanisms, structural and functional changes in cells and tissues. Applications: diagnosis, research, clinical medicine.

Pharmacology.description: Study of drugs and their effects on the body. Applications: medicine, drug development, therapeutics.

Immunogenetics.description: Study of genetic basis of immune system variation and disease susceptibility. Applications: autoimmune disease research, transplantation, personalized medicine.

Systems Biology.description: Study of complex interactions within biological systems using computational and mathematical modeling. Applications: disease modeling, drug development, synthetic biology.

Stem Cell Biology.description: Study of stem cells, their differentiation, and potential for regenerative medicine. Applications: tissue engineering, regenerative therapies, developmental studies.

Neurogenetics.description: Study of the genetic basis of nervous system development and function. Applications: neurological disease research, cognitive genetics, therapy development.

Organic Chemistry.description: Study of carbon-containing compounds. Includes alkanes, alkenes, alcohols, biomolecules. Applications: pharmaceuticals, materials, biochemistry.

Inorganic Chemistry.description: Study of non-carbon compounds: salts, metals, minerals. Applications: catalysts, materials science, coordination chemistry.

Physical Chemistry.description: Study of physical principles underlying chemical systems: thermodynamics, kinetics, quantum chemistry. Applications: reaction modeling, spectroscopy, materials science.

Analytical Chemistry.description: Techniques to identify and quantify chemical substances: spectroscopy, chromatography, titration. Applications: quality control, environmental analysis, forensics.

Electrochemistry.description: Chemical processes involving electron transfer. Applications: batteries, fuel cells, corrosion prevention.

Chemical Kinetics.description: Study of reaction rates and factors affecting them: concentration, temperature, catalysts. Applications: industrial chemistry, pharmacology, environmental science.

Thermochemistry.description: Study of heat changes in chemical reactions. Applications: energy efficiency, reaction design, combustion analysis.

Periodic Table.description: Organization of elements by atomic number, electron configuration, and properties. Groups: metals, non-metals, noble gases. Applications: chemistry education, element prediction, materials science.

Acid-Base Chemistry.description: Study of proton transfer reactions. Definitions: Brnsted-Lowry, Lewis. Applications: titration, buffer solutions, biochemistry.

Coordination Chemistry.description: Study of complexes formed between metal ions and ligands. Applications: catalysis, material design, bioinorganic chemistry.

Organometallic Chemistry.description: Study of compounds containing metal-carbon bonds. Applications: catalysis, pharmaceuticals, polymer synthesis.

Green Chemistry.description: Design of chemical processes to reduce environmental impact and waste. Applications: sustainable manufacturing, pollution control, renewable energy.

Supramolecular Chemistry.description: Study of molecular assemblies formed by non-covalent interactions. Applications: drug delivery, nanotechnology, material science.

Solid State Chemistry.description: Study of structure, properties, and reactions of solid materials. Applications: semiconductors, ceramics, battery materials.

Surface Chemistry.description: Study of chemical phenomena at surfaces and interfaces. Applications: catalysis, adsorption, nanomaterials.

Computational Chemistry.description: Use of computer simulations to solve chemical problems and predict molecular properties. Applications: drug design, materials modeling, quantum chemistry.

Nuclear Chemistry.description: Study of radioactive substances, nuclear reactions, and isotopes. Applications: medicine, energy, radiochemistry.

Photochemistry.description: Study of chemical reactions induced by light. Applications: solar energy, photosynthesis research, phototherapy.

Environmental Chemistry.description: Study of chemical processes in the environment, including pollutants and biogeochemical cycles. Applications: pollution control, water quality, climate research.

Pharmaceutical Chemistry.description: Design, synthesis, and analysis of drugs and medicinal compounds. Applications: drug development, therapeutics, pharmacology.

Analytical Spectroscopy.description: Study and application of spectroscopy methods to analyze chemical composition. Applications: quality control, forensic analysis, material characterization.

Chemical Thermodynamics.description: Study of energy and entropy changes in chemical reactions and processes. Applications: reaction prediction, material stability, process design.

Reaction Mechanisms.description: Investigation of step-by-step sequences of elementary reactions. Applications: catalysis, synthesis optimization, kinetic modeling.

Industrial Chemistry.description: Application of chemical principles to large-scale manufacturing processes. Applications: petrochemicals, polymers, fertilizers, pharmaceuticals.

Polymer Chemistry.description: Study of synthesis, structure, and properties of polymers. Applications: plastics, fibers, biomedical materials.

Anatomy.description: Study of structure of organisms and organs. Applications: medicine, surgery, physiology.

Cardiovascular Diseases.description: Disorders of heart and blood vessels: coronary artery disease, stroke, hypertension. Applications: diagnosis, treatment, prevention.

Diabetes.description: Metabolic disorder with high blood sugar due to insulin deficiency/resistance. Types: Type 1, Type 2, gestational. Applications: medical management, nutrition, pharmacology.

Infectious Diseases.description: Diseases caused by bacteria, viruses, parasites, fungi. Examples: influenza, malaria, COVID-19. Applications: vaccination, treatment, public health.

COVID-19.description: A contagious disease caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus. Symptoms: fever, cough, loss of taste/smell. Prevention: vaccination, masks, social distancing. Applications: epidemiology, public health, virology.

SARS-CoV-2.description: The virus responsible for COVID-19. It infects human respiratory cells and spreads via droplets. Applications: virology research, vaccine development.

Coronavirus.description: Family of viruses causing diseases in humans and animals. Some cause common cold, others like SARS and MERS are severe. Applications: epidemiology, virology, vaccine research.

Bacteria.description: Single-celled microorganisms that can be beneficial or pathogenic. Applications: medicine, biotechnology, microbiology.

Virus.description: Non-living infectious agents that require host cells to replicate. Applications: medicine, virology, epidemiology.

Immune System.description: Complex network of cells, tissues, and organs defending against pathogens. Components: white blood cells, antibodies, lymphatic system. Applications: immunology, vaccine development, disease prevention.

Mental Health.description: Study of psychological well-being and disorders: depression, anxiety, bipolar disorder. Applications: therapy, psychiatry, neuroscience.

Nutrition.description: Study of nutrients and dietary requirements for health. Applications: diet planning, public health, agriculture.

Cancer.description: Group of diseases characterized by uncontrolled cell growth. Types: carcinoma, sarcoma, leukemia. Applications: oncology, treatment research, early detection.

Respiratory Diseases.description: Diseases affecting lungs and airways: asthma, COPD, pneumonia. Applications: diagnosis, treatment, pulmonary medicine.

Neurological Disorders.description: Diseases of the nervous system: Alzheimers, Parkinsons, epilepsy. Applications: neurology, treatment research, cognitive science.

Vaccines.description: Biological preparations providing immunity to specific diseases. Applications: disease prevention, public health, epidemiology.

Genetic Disorders.description: Diseases caused by abnormalities in genes or chromosomes: cystic fibrosis, sickle cell anemia. Applications: genetics, prenatal diagnosis, therapy research.

Nephrology.description: Study of kidney function, structure, and diseases. Applications: dialysis, hypertension management, renal transplantation.

Hepatology.description: Study of liver, gallbladder, biliary tree, and associated diseases. Applications: liver disease treatment, transplantation, hepatology research.

Gastroenterology.description: Study of digestive system structure, function, and disorders. Applications: treatment of ulcers, IBS, liver and pancreatic diseases.

Immunopathology.description: Study of immune system disorders and abnormal immune responses. Applications: autoimmune disease management, allergy treatment, immunotherapy.

Infectious Disease Epidemiology.description: Study of patterns, causes, and effects of infectious diseases in populations. Applications: outbreak control, vaccination programs, public health policy.

Pulmonology.description: Study of respiratory system structure, function, and diseases. Applications: asthma, COPD management, respiratory therapy.

Rheumatology.description: Study of musculoskeletal and autoimmune disorders affecting joints and connective tissues. Applications: arthritis treatment, autoimmune disease research.

Oncogenetics.description: Study of genetic basis of cancer development and progression. Applications: targeted therapy, risk assessment, precision medicine.

Reproductive Medicine.description: Study of reproductive system health, fertility, and related disorders. Applications: IVF, contraception, endocrinology.

Neuropsychiatry.description: Study of mental disorders with neurological basis. Applications: treatment of depression, bipolar disorder, neurocognitive disorders.

Gerontology.description: Study of aging and age-related diseases. Applications: elder care, chronic disease management, research on longevity.

Obstetrics.description: Medical specialty dealing with pregnancy, childbirth, and postpartum care. Applications: maternal health, prenatal diagnostics, labor management.

Gynecology.description: Study of female reproductive system health, disorders, and treatments. Applications: reproductive health, cancer screening, hormonal therapies.

Critical Care Medicine.description: Specialty focused on life-threatening conditions requiring intensive monitoring and intervention. Applications: ICU management, emergency treatment, trauma care.

Photosynthesis in Plants.description: Conversion of sunlight, CO2, and water into glucose and oxygen using chlorophyll. Applications: agriculture, bioenergy, ecology.

Plant Anatomy.description: Study of plant structure: roots, stems, leaves, flowers. Applications: botany, agriculture, forestry.

Plant Physiology.description: Study of plant function: growth, transpiration, respiration, hormone regulation. Applications: agriculture, horticulture, biotechnology.

Plant Ecology.description: Interactions of plants with environment and other organisms. Applications: conservation, forestry, climate studies.

Botanical Genetics.description: Study of inheritance in plants. Applications: crop improvement, genetic engineering.

Plant Biotechnology.description: Application of technology to modify or enhance plants. Applications: GMOs, pharmaceuticals, agriculture.

Soil-Plant Interaction.description: Study of nutrient uptake, water absorption, and soil chemistry. Applications: agriculture, environmental science.

Plant Pathology.description: Study of plant diseases caused by pathogens (fungi, bacteria, viruses) and environmental conditions. Applications: crop protection, disease management, agriculture.

Plant Nutrition.description: Study of essential nutrients required for plant growth and development. Applications: fertilizer design, soil management, sustainable agriculture.

Plant Molecular Biology.description: Study of molecular mechanisms controlling plant growth, development, and stress responses. Applications: genetic engineering, crop improvement, biotechnology.

Plant Development.description: Study of growth processes and developmental stages of plants from germination to maturity. Applications: horticulture, agriculture, developmental genetics.

Plant Hormones.description: Study of chemical messengers regulating plant growth and responses (auxins, gibberellins, cytokinins). Applications: crop yield improvement, tissue culture, plant breeding.

Ethnobotany.description: Study of the relationship between plants and human cultures, including traditional uses. Applications: pharmacology, conservation, sustainable resource management.

Agroecology.description: Study of ecological processes applied to agricultural production systems. Applications: sustainable farming, soil health, biodiversity conservation.

Plant Systematics.description: Study of plant classification, taxonomy, and evolutionary relationships. Applications: biodiversity studies, conservation, phylogenetics.

Plant Physiology under Stress.description: Study of plant responses to abiotic stresses such as drought, salinity, and temperature extremes. Applications: crop resilience, climate adaptation, biotechnology.

Seed Biology.description: Study of seed development, dormancy, germination, and viability. Applications: agriculture, forestry, seed banking.

Plant Biotechnology in Tissue Culture.description: Use of in vitro techniques to propagate plants or produce genetically modified plants. Applications: mass propagation, genetic engineering, pharmaceutical production.

Plant-Microbe Interactions.description: Study of symbiotic and pathogenic relationships between plants and microorganisms. Applications: nitrogen fixation, disease resistance, soil health.

Algorithm.description: Step-by-step procedure for solving problems or computations. Applications: programming, optimization, AI.

Data Structures.description: Organized formats to store and manage data: arrays, lists, trees, graphs. Applications: programming, databases, algorithms.

Artificial Intelligence.description: Simulation of human intelligence in machines. Applications: NLP, computer vision, robotics.

Machine Learning.description: Algorithms that improve from data without explicit programming. Applications: recommendation systems, predictive modeling, image recognition.

Deep Learning.description: Subset of machine learning using neural networks with multiple layers. Applications: speech recognition, computer vision, autonomous vehicles.

Databases.description: Structured storage of data: relational (SQL), non-relational (NoSQL). Applications: data management, analytics, enterprise systems.

Big Data.description: Processing and analysis of massive datasets. Applications: business intelligence, scientific research, AI.

Computer Networks.description: Study of interconnected systems exchanging data. Applications: internet, cybersecurity, communications.

Cybersecurity.description: Protection of computer systems and networks from attacks. Applications: encryption, secure communication, threat detection.

Programming Languages.description: Formal languages used to implement algorithms: Python, C++, Java. Applications: software development, data analysis.

Operating Systems.description: Software that manages hardware resources and provides services for computer programs. Applications: process management, memory management, file systems, multitasking.

Computer Architecture.description: Study of the structure, organization, and design of computer systems. Applications: CPU design, hardware optimization, embedded systems.

Software Engineering.description: Application of engineering principles to software development. Applications: system design, testing, maintenance, large-scale software projects.

Cloud Computing.description: Delivery of computing resources over the internet. Applications: scalable storage, SaaS platforms, distributed computing.

Data Mining.description: Process of discovering patterns and knowledge from large datasets. Applications: marketing analytics, fraud detection, scientific research.

Natural Language Processing.description: Field of AI focused on interaction between computers and human language. Applications: chatbots, language translation, sentiment analysis.

Computer Vision.description: Field enabling machines to interpret and process visual information. Applications: facial recognition, autonomous vehicles, medical imaging.

Human-Computer Interaction.description: Study of interfaces and interactions between humans and computers. Applications: UX design, accessibility, interactive systems.

Distributed Systems.description: Study of multiple computers working together to achieve a common goal. Applications: cloud services, blockchain, parallel computing.

Robotics.description: Design, construction, and operation of robots. Applications: manufacturing automation, autonomous vehicles, surgery.

Embedded Systems.description: Computers integrated into devices for dedicated functions. Applications: IoT devices, automotive control systems, industrial automation.

Data Science.description: Interdisciplinary field using scientific methods to extract knowledge from data. Applications: predictive modeling, business intelligence, research analytics.

Reinforcement Learning.description: Machine learning paradigm where agents learn optimal actions via rewards and penalties. Applications: robotics, game AI, autonomous systems.

Computer Graphics.description: Creation and manipulation of visual content using computers. Applications: video games, simulations, animation, VR/AR.

Blockchain.description: Decentralized ledger technology enabling secure transactions. Applications: cryptocurrency, supply chain, secure data management.

Mechanical Engineering.description: Design, analysis, and manufacturing of mechanical systems. Applications: engines, machinery, robotics.

Electrical Engineering.description: Study and application of electricity, electronics, and electromagnetism. Applications: circuits, power systems, electronics.

Civil Engineering.description: Design, construction, and maintenance of infrastructure: buildings, bridges, roads. Applications: urban planning, transportation, structural safety.

Chemical Engineering.description: Application of chemistry, physics, biology to process design and production. Applications: pharmaceuticals, energy, materials.

Materials Science.description: Study of material properties, structure, and applications. Applications: aerospace, electronics, construction.

Environmental Engineering.description: Application of engineering to improve and protect the environment. Applications: water treatment, pollution control, sustainability.

Control Systems.description: Design of systems to regulate processes automatically. Applications: robotics, manufacturing, automotive systems.

Thermodynamics (Engineering).description: Study of energy conversion and heat transfer in engineering systems. Applications: engines, HVAC, refrigeration.

Aerospace Engineering.description: Design, development, and testing of aircraft, spacecraft, and related systems. Applications: aviation, satellite technology, space exploration.

Industrial Engineering.description: Optimization of complex systems, processes, and organizations. Applications: manufacturing efficiency, logistics, supply chain management.

Structural Engineering.description: Specialty of civil engineering focusing on the design and analysis of structures. Applications: buildings, bridges, tunnels, earthquake-resistant structures.

Mechanical Design.description: Study of creating mechanical systems and components using engineering principles. Applications: machinery, automotive design, consumer products.

Instrumentation Engineering.description: Design and maintenance of instruments for measuring and controlling physical quantities. Applications: automation, medical devices, industrial monitoring.

Robotics Engineering.description: Design, construction, and operation of robots and automated systems. Applications: manufacturing automation, surgery, autonomous vehicles.

Nanotechnology.description: Manipulation and engineering of materials at atomic and molecular scales. Applications: electronics, materials development, biomedical devices.

Mechatronics.description: Integration of mechanical, electrical, and computer engineering for intelligent systems. Applications: robotics, automation, smart devices.

Energy Engineering.description: Study of energy production, conversion, and management. Applications: renewable energy, power plants, energy efficiency.

Automotive Engineering.description: Design, development, and manufacturing of vehicles. Applications: car design, fuel efficiency, electric and autonomous vehicles.

Structural Materials.description: Study of mechanical and chemical properties of materials used in construction. Applications: bridges, buildings, aerospace structures.

Petroleum Engineering.description: Exploration, extraction, and production of oil and gas resources. Applications: energy industry, drilling technology, reservoir management.

Water Resources Engineering.description: Design and management of water systems, including dams, irrigation, and flood control. Applications: urban planning, agriculture, environmental sustainability.

Marine Engineering.description: Design and maintenance of ships, offshore structures, and marine equipment. Applications: shipping, offshore energy, naval architecture.

Geology.description: Study of Earth's solid materials, structures, and processes. Applications: mining, oil exploration, natural disaster prediction.

Meteorology.description: Science of atmosphere and weather phenomena. Applications: weather forecasting, climate studies, disaster preparedness.

Oceanography.description: Study of oceans, currents, ecosystems, and chemistry. Applications: marine conservation, navigation, climate research.

Plate Tectonics.description: Theory explaining Earth's lithosphere divided into plates. Responsible for earthquakes, volcanoes, mountain formation.

Astronomy.description: Study of celestial objects and the universe. Applications: astrophysics, navigation, cosmology.

Astrobiology.description: Study of life in the universe, including origins and conditions for life. Applications: space exploration, exoplanet research.

Exoplanets.description: Planets orbiting stars outside our solar system. Detected via transit and radial velocity methods. Importance: habitability research.

Cosmic Microwave Background.description: Relic radiation from early universe. Provides evidence for Big Bang and universe structure formation.

Seismology.description: Study of earthquakes and propagation of seismic waves through Earth. Applications: earthquake prediction, structural engineering, geophysics.

Volcanology.description: Study of volcanoes, magma, and related geological phenomena. Applications: hazard assessment, eruption prediction, geothermal energy.

Geophysics.description: Application of physics to study Earth's interior, magnetic and gravitational fields. Applications: resource exploration, earthquake studies, geodesy.

Hydrology.description: Study of water movement, distribution, and quality on Earth. Applications: water resource management, flood control, environmental planning.

Climatology.description: Study of climate systems, patterns, and long-term atmospheric behavior. Applications: climate change research, policy planning, environmental science.

Geomorphology.description: Study of landforms, their processes, history, and evolution. Applications: erosion control, landscape management, hazard assessment.

Planetary Science.description: Study of planets, moons, and planetary systems, including formation and evolution. Applications: space exploration, exoplanet research, solar system studies.

Space Weather.description: Study of conditions in space caused by solar activity affecting Earth and its environment. Applications: satellite operations, communication, power grid protection.

Astroparticle Physics.description: Study of particles from space and their interactions with matter. Applications: cosmic rays, dark matter detection, neutrino astronomy.

Galactic Astronomy.description: Study of structure and dynamics of galaxies, including the Milky Way. Applications: galaxy formation, cosmology, stellar evolution.

Observational Astronomy.description: Acquisition and analysis of data from telescopes and instruments. Applications: astrophysics research, exoplanet detection, celestial mapping.

Radio Astronomy.description: Study of celestial objects using radio waves. Applications: pulsars, cosmic microwave background, interstellar medium research.

Economics.description: Study of production, distribution, and consumption of goods and services. Branches: microeconomics, macroeconomics.

Psychology.description: Scientific study of behavior and mental processes. Branches: cognitive, clinical, social psychology.

Sociology.description: Study of society, social relationships, and institutions. Applications: policy, education, urban planning.

Political Science.description: Study of governments, political behavior, policies, and systems. Applications: diplomacy, governance, international relations.

Linguistics.description: Scientific study of language, structure, meaning, and context. Branches: phonetics, syntax, semantics, pragmatics.

Philosophy.description: Study of fundamental questions about existence, knowledge, ethics, and reasoning. Applications: ethics, logic, critical thinking.

History.description: Study of past events and human civilization. Applications: education, cultural understanding, research.

Anthropology.description: Study of humans, societies, cultures, and evolution. Applications: archaeology, sociology, cultural studies.

Archaeology.description: Study of human history and prehistory through excavation and analysis of artifacts and structures. Applications: cultural heritage preservation, historical research, anthropology.

Human Geography.description: Study of human activities, cultures, and their relationship with the environment. Applications: urban planning, migration studies, resource management.

Ethics.description: Philosophical study of morality, right and wrong, and human conduct. Applications: bioethics, business ethics, legal frameworks.

Education.description: Study of teaching methods, learning processes, and educational systems. Applications: curriculum design, pedagogy, policy development.

International Relations.description: Study of interactions between nations, including diplomacy, conflict, and cooperation. Applications: global policy, peace studies, security analysis.

Law.description: System of rules created and enforced by institutions to regulate behavior. Applications: legal practice, governance, human rights.

Archaeogenetics.description: Study of ancient DNA to understand human history and migration. Applications: anthropology, population studies, evolutionary biology.

Cultural Studies.description: Analysis of cultural phenomena in societal contexts, including media, traditions, and norms. Applications: sociology, media studies, globalization research.

Media Studies.description: Study of media production, content, and its social impact. Applications: journalism, communications, cultural influence analysis.

Development Studies.description: Examination of social, economic, and political development in societies. Applications: poverty alleviation, policy-making, sustainable development.

Archaeometry.description: Application of scientific techniques to analyze archaeological artifacts. Applications: dating artifacts, material analysis, preservation.

Religious Studies.description: Study of religious beliefs, practices, and institutions. Applications: theology, comparative religion, anthropology.

Urban Studies.description: Study of urbanization, city planning, and social dynamics in urban environments. Applications: infrastructure development, policy planning, community studies.

Gender Studies.description: Examination of gender roles, identity, and relations in society. Applications: equality research, social policy, cultural studies.

Criminology.description: Study of crime, criminal behavior, and the justice system. Applications: law enforcement, rehabilitation programs, policy development.
